WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.100
So I'll be presenting on a very early phase two study that very early phase two study just open.

00:00:13.100 --> 00:00:20.520
We don't have any patients on study yet, but looking at Glofidamab after CD19-directed CAR-T cell therapy for mantle cell lymphoma.

00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:25.520
Here are my disclosures and objectives.

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.640
There are two approved CAR-T products for mantle cell.

00:00:29.740 --> 00:00:38.300
We have Brexu cell, CD28 co-stimulatory domain, and Lysa cell, the 401BB co-stimulatory domain.

00:00:39.120 --> 00:00:47.740
Each of these have been studied as therapies showing good overall response rates, but limited durability.

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:55.300
So in ZUMA2, we know that Brexu cell led to an overall response rate of 91%, complete response in 68%.

00:00:55.300 --> 00:00:59.300
But as we're getting further out from therapy, we're seeing that many of these patients are relapsing.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:03.660
And at three years, only 37% with an ongoing response.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:08.300
This is the three-year follow-up of this data.

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:15.420
The all-comers represented by the purple line, those with a complete response represented by the blue line.

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:24.860
And even patients who had a complete response as we're getting out to four years or so, really less than half of these patients are still alive and without relapse.

00:01:27.220 --> 00:01:29.340
Really no obvious predictors.

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:45.880
Here, regardless of TP53 status, K67, and others, there is some data that CAR-T peak levels do predict or give us some indication of patients that are going to have lasting responses.

00:01:46.660 --> 00:01:51.000
So those who don't respond really have, as expected, very low levels of peak CAR-T.

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:59.000
MRD is, I think, perhaps less effective here as a definitive answer for really determining who's going to relapse.

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:04.700
And who's not, this is using Clonaseq, but perhaps more sensitive assays will be useful in the future.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:14.680
And we do see that even out to 18 and 24 months, that many patients who have ongoing responses do have detectable CAR-T cells.

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:19.680
So 70% and 67% at 18 and 24 months, respectively.

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:25.560
Switching gears to Lysa cell, overall a similar story.

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:28.960
We're seeing most patients respond, 83% response rate.

00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:31.560
With complete response at 72%.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:35.400
Median duration of response is still under 16 months.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:38.560
So again, most patients are losing that response.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:41.380
Slightly lower rates of CRS and ICANS.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:47.980
Here's the progression-free survival and duration of response data for Lysa cell.

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:59.400
And importantly, we now have data that patients that relapse after CAR-T do especially poorly.

00:02:59.460 --> 00:03:06.740
So there were two retrospective studies presented at ASH this past year, and that led to two publications, both in blood advances, shortly afterward.

00:03:07.460 --> 00:03:14.160
This is a multi-center study, retrospective study, looking at 133 patients who relapsed after CAR-T for mantle cell.

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:20.720
I think it was 87% of these patients that had Brexu cell, the remainder having Lysa cell.

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:28.660
And under six months overall survival from the time of relapsing after CAR-T, and that's regardless of treatment as a whole.

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:39.100
When we look at breaking this down further into time of relapse, I think not surprisingly, those who relapse sooner have very poor prognosis.

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:46.800
So those who relapse within three months, really it's about a three-month, somewhere between a two- and three-month overall survival.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:53.100
Slightly better chances for those who have relapses at three to six months, and better for those who have later relapses.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:59.360
When we look at which therapies are effective in this setting, I think as a whole,

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:06.780
it's generally disappointing when we're looking at single agents that are often effective in this patient population prior to CAR-T.

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:12.400
The one therapy as a monotherapy that does seem to be effective are the Bispecific.

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:20.380
So most of these have been Bofidamab that have been studied, small numbers, so 12 patients, but two-thirds responded with a complete response.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:29.340
There are also some patients that receive combination therapies with some of the small molecules, so Selmides, BCL-2 inhibitors,

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:34.680
and BTK inhibitors that did have some evidence of response as well.

00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:46.840
Similarly, there was a French registration study looking at patients after Brexacel specifically who relapsed with generally a very similar story here.

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:55.440
They also saw that the T-cell engaging therapies, again, mostly represented by, I think in this case, all Glufidamab, I believe,

00:04:56.020 --> 00:04:59.060
did seem to be the best opportunity for a response.

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:02.340
With very low response rates in other therapies.

00:05:04.780 --> 00:05:14.840
We designed this study initially about four years ago with using Glufidamab in combination with another therapy as a consolidation after CAR-T to prevent relapse,

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:16.820
a concept I still favor.

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:21.120
But for reasons that are outside of my control, these things change.

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:26.440
And ultimately, it was repurposed as a salvage therapy given lack of data in that setting.

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:29.300
And so part of our goal here really is...

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:34.100
is to establish the efficacy to determine the impact on CAR-T cells

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:39.900
and to see if we might use this alone or in combination as a consolidation strategy in the future.

00:05:41.320 --> 00:05:42.960
This is the study design.

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:52.740
We'll be using Obinutuzumab, the higher dose, as previously discussed, of two grams per meter squared on cycle one, day one,

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:55.940
followed by Glufidamab step-up dosing, as has been described.

00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:59.300
We'll also be looking at CAR-T cell levels.

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:07.980
As well as immunophenotypes, the CD4 to CD8 ratio, potential markers of exhaustion, LAG3, TIM3, PD-L1,

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:14.380
and seeing if we might have some impact on CAR-T exhaustion as well as cytotoxic markers.

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:22.040
Future directions in this setting, I think, again, the maintenance or consolidation approach is preferred to a salvage therapy,

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:24.040
ideally with some of these combinations.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:26.000
There is some data.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.280
There was a TARMAC study that came out of Australia looking at...

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:33.500
ibrutinib prior to cell collection and throughout CAR-T cell.

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:40.740
I think they were using Tissa cell in that study for mantle cell lymphoma with some promising results.

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.400
There are also dual-targeted CAR-T cells.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:50.380
There was a publication, I believe, in December of this year coming out of Wisconsin using a CD20, CD19-directed CAR-T product.

00:06:50.940 --> 00:06:54.020
Early follow-up, but overall looks to be promising.

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:57.280
Hopefully, some options for improving outcomes in these patients.

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:01.980
With that, I thank you all for your time and happy to take questions.
